Yes, Rohan â€” running that eksctl create iamidentitymapping command should absolutely resolve the issue you're facing with kubectl access. Even though the cluster is already created, the identity mapping step is what bridges your IAM role to Kubernetes RBAC.

âœ… Why This Will Fix Your Problem
	â€¢ Your GitHub Actions runner is assuming an IAM role (GitHubActionsEKSRole), which has AWS access.
	â€¢ But Kubernetes doesn't recognize that IAM role unless it's mapped in the aws-auth ConfigMap.
	â€¢ By running: 
eksctl create iamidentitymapping \
  --cluster dev-cluster \
  --region us-east-1 \
  --arn arn:aws:iam::<your-account-id>:role/GitHubActionsEKSRole \
  --username github-actions \
  --group system:masters

you're telling EKS: â€œThis IAM role is allowed to act as a Kubernetes user with system-level access.â€

ğŸ” Bonus Validation Tip
After running the command, try:
kubectl get configmap aws-auth -n kube-system -o yaml
You should see a new entry under mapRoles: with the role you added.

Once this is in place, rerunning your GitHub Actions workflow should show kubectl outputs like:
	â€¢ kubectl get pods -A
	â€¢ kubectl get secrets -A
	â€¢ kubectl get nodes
